  "local_port": 58574,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I add a floating chart (like freezing top row) in Excel 2013?",
  "response": "To add a floating chart (similar to freezing the top row) in Excel 2013, we can use a combination of a chart and a scrollable data range. This approach will allow the chart to remain visible while the underlying data can be scrolled. Here's how to achieve this:\n\n1. **Create your chart:**\n   First, you need to create your chart based on the data you want to analyze. Select your data range and insert the chart type you prefer (e.g., column, line, etc.).\n\n2. **Move the chart to a separate sheet:**\n   - Right-click on the chart and select \"Move Chart\".\n   - In the dialog box, choose \"New sheet\" and give it a name (e.g., \"Floating Chart\").\n\n3. **Set up the data range:**\n   - Go back to your original data sheet.\n   - Create a named range for the data you want to chart. This will allow you to reference it easily in your chart.\n     - Select the data range.\n     - Go to the \"Formulas\" tab, click \"Define Name\", and give your range a name (e.g., \"ChartData\").\n\n4. **Link the chart to the named range:**\n   - Go to your \"Floating Chart\" sheet.\n   - Right-click on the chart and choose \"Select Data\".\n   - In the \"Select Data Source\" dialog, change the chart data range to refer to your named range (e.g., `=Sheet1!ChartData`).\n\n5. **Add scroll bars to the data sheet:**\n   - Go back to your data sheet.\n   - We'll use form controls to create scroll bars. Go to the \"Developer\" tab. If you don't see it, you need to enable it:\n     - File > Options > Customize Ribbon > Check \"Developer\" in the right pane.\n   - In the Developer tab, click \"Insert\" > \"Scroll Bar\" (under Form Controls).\n   - Draw the scroll bar where you want it on your sheet.\n\n6. **Link the scroll bars to your data:**\n   - Right-click on the scroll bar and choose \"Format Control\".\n   - In the \"Control\" tab, set the following:\n     - Current value: The starting row of your visible data range.\n     - Minimum value: 1 (or the first row of your full data range).\n     - Maximum value: The last row of your full data range minus the number of rows you want to show.\n     - Incremental change: 1 (to move one row at a time).\n     - Page change: The number of rows you want to scroll at once.\n   - In the \"Cell link\" field, choose a cell (e.g., A1) that will store the current value of the scroll bar.\n\n7. **Create a dynamic range for your chart:**\n   - Use the OFFSET function to create a dynamic range that changes based on the scroll bar position.\n   - In a cell outside your data range (e.g., A2), enter this formula:\n     ```\n     =OFFSET(Sheet1!$A$1,A1,0,10,5)\n     ```\n     This assumes your data starts in A1, you're scrolling 10 rows at a time, and your data has 5 columns. Adjust as needed.\n\n8. **Update your named range:**\n   - Go to \"Formulas\" > \"Name Manager\".\n   - Edit your \"ChartData\" range to use the cell with the OFFSET formula (e.g., `=Sheet1!$A$2`).\n\nNow, when you scroll using the scroll bar, the chart on the \"Floating Chart\" sheet will update to show the new data range while remaining visible.\n\nThis method effectively creates a floating chart similar to freezing the top row, allowing you to scroll through your data while keeping the chart in view.",
